Thats a smart instinct but also a common misconception. Let me break it down honestly so you know exactly what you can do, what wont work, and what will give you the best ROI.

The Truth About SEO (Search Engine Optimization)

What You Want:

When someone searches anything about hay or feeding horses, I want my site to show up at the top.

What That Actually Takes:

To rank high on Google, especially for competitive searches like hay near me or horse hay delivery, Google needs to see:

  • Relevant content (pages with real info, not just a placeholder)

  • Activity (updates, links, reviews, etc.)

  • Authority (time online, backlinks from other reputable sites)

A single one-page site wont outrank established sellers

Sites like Tractor Supply, Feed Stores, Craigslist listings, etc. will always show up first unless you get very niche or local.

What You Can Realistically Do (That Works):

1. Dominate Local SEO

Instead of trying to rank for all hay-related terms, focus on:

  • Alfalfa hay in [your area]

  • Horse hay near [your town]

  • Hay delivery [your county]

These are easier to win.

How?

  • Claim and optimize your Google Business Profile
    (Go to google.com/business)

  • Use keywords like:

    arduino
    We sell premium alfalfa and bermuda hay for horses, goats, and livestock in [Your City, State].
Pickup and delivery available.

  • Add these terms to your HTML (I can do that for you)

  • Get Google Reviews from customers. These help tremendously.

2. Boost Facebook SEO

You already use Facebook make sure:

  • Your business location info is filled out

  • Posts use keywords: "horse hay", "bermuda", "alfalfa", "delivery", "pickup", etc.

  • You post often (weekly is enough)

  • You get reviews on Facebook

3. Optional: Add More Content Later

If you ever want to go beyond one page:

  • Add a second page for FAQs or What kind of hay do I need?

  • Add a blog post like How to store hay properly or What kind of hay is best for horses?

Even one of these can move you up in Google rankings over time.

Lets Get Your Website Live with Cloudflare Pages

Youll need:

  • A Cloudflare account (you already have one if your domain is there)

  • The final HTML file (you already have it!)

  • A GitHub account (needed to connect to Cloudflare Pages free and fast)

Step-by-Step Instructions:

1. Create a GitHub Account (if you dont already have one)

  • Go to https://github.com/join

  • Its free. Youll use it just to upload your HTML file.

2. Create a New GitHub Repository

  • After logging in, go to: https://github.com/new

  • Name it something like equine-depot-site

  • Set it to Public

  • Check Add a README file

  • Click Create Repository

3. Upload Your Files

  1. Go to your new repo.

  2. Click Add file > Upload files

  3. Upload:

    • the_equine_depot_site_FINAL_with_logo.html

    • logo_actual.png

  4. Click Commit changes at the bottom

Then, rename your HTML file:

  • Click the filename (the_equine_depot_site_FINAL_with_logo.html)

  • Click the pencil icon to edit

  • Rename it to:
    index.html (this is important it makes the page load at your domain)

Click Commit changes again.

4. Set Up Cloudflare Pages

  1. Go to https://pages.cloudflare.com

  2. Click Create a Project

  3. Connect your GitHub account

  4. Select the repository you just made

  5. On the setup screen:

    • Framework preset: Choose None

    • Build command: leave blank

    • Output folder: type . (just a period)

Click Save and Deploy

5. Connect Your Domain (www.theequinedepot.com)

Once Cloudflare Pages deploys your site, youll get a link like https://equine-depot-site.pages.dev

To use your real domain:

  1. In Cloudflare Dashboard, go to your domain (theequinedepot.com)

  2. Go to the Pages tab

  3. Click Custom domains

  4. Add www.theequinedepot.com

  5. Follow the prompt to create the CNAME record (Cloudflare can do it automatically)

Thats it within minutes, your site will be live at:

https://www.theequinedepot.com
